features.merge_signal_comment: mbelinky: Merging into new alpha code path

errors.reasoning: Terminal positive merge signal: Contributor mbelinky (CONTRIBUTOR role) explicitly states 'Merging into new alpha code path' with cherry-pick attribution preserved. This is a commit-hash-backed merge receipt equivalent (P-2-2: explicit merge language from a contributor). Despite first-time contributor status (0 prior PRs) and XS size, the merge receipt comment overrides all negative signals. Category: app-level security hardening (ATS). Small scope (2 files, focused).

First-time contributor (0 prior PRs, 0% merge rate) with large feature PR (21 files, L-sized) touching Matrix extension with multi-account refactor. High engagement (43 comments, iterative fixes) but all comments are author self-advocacy and greptile automated reviews. Greptile flags 3 distinct architectural bugs: (1) stopSharedClient() with no key stops ALL shared clients, (2) wrong account client selection in resolveMatrixClient, (3) accountId ignored for shared auth. Author responds to comments but greptile keeps flagging issues across multiple rounds, suggesting the implementation has structural problems. Zero human reviewer approvals, no maintainer label, community comment notes original issue (#5292) not fixed. Pattern P-4-1 applies: XL-sized PR from first-time contributor without human reviewer approval/maintainer label = unlikely merge. Multiple architectural issues flagged by AI reviewer compound the non-merge signal. The iterative cycle without resolution suggests the PR is problematic.

First-time contributor (0 prior PRs) with a focused docs PR. However, 0 files changed reported despite listing 6 files in the description—this is a data anomaly suggesting a malformed PR or metadata error. Additionally, the Greptile comment identifies a structural documentation issue (incorrect nesting of security mode as an enum value), and no human reviewer (only Greptile bot and a cryptic comment from sergiopesch) has approved or engaged substantively. Per P-5-5 and P-1-7, first-time contributors with zero reviews and data inconsistencies have low merge probability.

First-time contributor (0 prior PRs) with M-sized PR (8 files, multi-category: gateway/commands/agents). Critical bug fix addressing contextWindow collision across providers—high-value fix. Member comment from sebslight (similar to approval closure pattern) without explicit rejection. Has both greptile and copilot reviews (automated + AI). No explicit non-merge signal. Matches high-engagement pattern (3 comments). Despite 0% author history, the technical significance and member engagement push toward merge. Confidence tempered by lack of human approval comment—requires mature-phase signals to exceed 0.75.

First-time contributor (0 prior PRs) with focused, critical fix (setTimeout overflow prevention for gateway hang). Medium scope (3 files, gateway + agents + tests). Tests present. Author provided clear rationale and marked as complementary to PR #10355. No explicit maintainer approval or label, but the technical necessity of the fix (preventing gateway hang from 32-bit overflow) and the presence of tests/CI reviews provide moderate confidence. Per P-6-1, first-time contributors with focused scope and tests but no human reviewer approval have low-to-moderate merge probability; the critical nature of the fix slightly elevates this.

Human reviewer (asklee-klawd) APPROVED with enthusiastic endorsement: '37% startup time reduction', 'Smart guard', 'Thoroughly tested (5642 tests)'. XS-sized focused performance optimization with human approval overrides author's 0% merge rate on 2 prior PRs. Approval from non-maintainer is present but no maintainer label. High-quality technical merit with human validation supports merge prediction.

Author coygeek has low merge rate (21 prior PRs, 3 merged, 14.3% merge rate = low-merge author). PR addresses critical security issue (loopback auth bypass in BlueBubbles) with active reviewer engagement (asklee-klawd and 0xRaini both provided substantive positive technical comments). However, three critical concerns: (1) Community contributor comments (jacobhaug) raise fundamental technical questions about BlueBubbles webhook auth support, suggesting potential design conflict. (2) No maintainer label or maintainer explicit approval comment. (3) Low author merge rate combined with complex security-sensitive code. Pattern P-7: 'XL-sized PRs from first-time contributors without maintainer labels are unlikely to merge' doesn't apply here (not first-time, not XL), but the low merge rate + lack of maintainer engagement on security fix + unresolved technical questions from contributors = non-merge signal. Security fixes require explicit maintainer sign-off; positive tech reviews from non-maintainers are insufficient.

First-time contributor (0 prior PRs, 0% merge rate) with focused security fix (file permissions). XS-sized PR (7 files), but crosses multiple components (agents, gateway, web-ui). Tests likely present given file naming (security-focused fix usually requires tests). Only automated Greptile review, no human reviewer approval or maintainer label. Per P-6-7, XS doc-only PRs with 100% prior merge rate from single PR still need human reviewer engagement; security fixes are more critical but this first-timer still lacks explicit approval. Modest positive signal from focused scope and security importance, but no maintainer engagement reduces confidence below 0.70.

First-time contributor (0 prior PRs, 0% merge rate) with XS-sized PR (7 files, agents category, feature addition: messages.suppressToolErrors config). No comments, no human reviews, no approval, no maintainer label, no maintainer engagement. Greptile did not provide review comment. While the PR touches multiple config/type files and includes test coverage (payloads.e2e.test.ts), the complete absence of human engagement (zero comments, zero reviews, zero approvals) is a terminal non-merge signal for first-time contributors. Pattern P-8: 'PRs with no reviews and no comments from first-time contributors, even with tests and focused scope, have low merge probability.' No human reviewer engagement + first-time contributor = non-merge prediction.

First-time contributor (0 prior PRs, 0% merge rate) with XL-sized PR (11 files, scripts category, new /export-session command). CRITICAL TERMINAL SIGNAL: steipete (CONTRIBUTOR) comment states 'We accidentally merged a batch of PRs and need to temporarily roll this back for now. Revert details: - merged commit SHA: [blank] - revert commit SHA: [blank]'. Pattern P-5-3: 'PRs where a maintainer comment confirms the PR was merged accidentally and subsequently reverted are not in a merged state for prediction purposes... Treat 'merged accidentally, reverted' language as equivalent to non-merge.' Despite positive prior engagement (boris721 addressed review feedback in commits b3ac287, 6b39002), the explicit revert statement from steipete overrides all positive signals. This is a terminal non-merge signal. The fact that commit hashes are blank in the visible excerpt does not negate the explicit revert language.

Member shakkernerd explicitly stated: 'Reverting this PR because it was merged accidentally. Revert commits: - d8a76282d - dd69fc0ad'. Per P-2-4 pattern: 'PRs where a maintainer comment confirms the PR was merged accidentally and subsequently reverted are not in a merged state for prediction purposes.' The revert statement is a terminal non-merge signal overriding all positive signals including the fact of a prior merge event. Treat as non-merged. First-time contributor with XS scope and only 1 file changed is irrelevant given the explicit revert.

Author saurabhchopade has strong track record: 1 prior PR, 1 merged (100% merge rate). Small-sized change (4 files, S label). Focused scope (preserves plugin-normalized IDs for message target resolution). Greptile review completed with 1 comment. No negative signals (not draft, no closure comments, no maintainer objections). Author association appears neutral but merge history is perfect. Focused scope and positive prior history support merge prediction, though lack of explicit maintainer approval or label introduces some uncertainty.
